messages.text: Mom, WTH is this?
What are you talking about, sweetheart?
Rebecca sends Mom a picture of a gnome sitting on the kitchen counter.
Oh, that!
Isn’t it cute?
No, it’s creepy.
Well, you’d better be good, because it’s watching you 😂
Is that supposed to be funny?
Mom, this isn’t funny.
Come on! I’m hilarious.
Look, it’s just a cute little thing I want to start doing for the holiday.
Like that elf on the shelf all the kids have.
Except you bought a knock-off version and it’s terrifying.
I’m pretty sure it’s staring right into my soul.
And it wants to murder me.
Don’t be dramatic, honey.
Seriously.
Those beady black eyes.
The scary-sharp red hat.
Those sinister, tiny little feet.
Like I said…
Better be good or you won’t get any presents!
Or maybe you’ll wake up one night and it’ll be standing over your bed!
MOM!
Joking! I’m joking!
Rebecca looks up from her phone. The gnome is gone.
Wait, are you messing with me right now?!
Honey, the gnome is just a silly tradition I want to start.
Stop getting yourself all worked up.
No, it’s not that.
It’s GONE.
Where did it go?
I don’t know. It’s like it got up and ran away!
One second it was there…
But then I looked down, and now it’s gone.
That’s impossible.
This isn’t funny.
I know it’s not funny.
If you did something with that gnome, you’re going to be in trouble.
That thing was ridiculously expensive.
Mom, I could care less about how much the freaking gnome cost right now.
It’s GONE.
It left all by itself!
Maybe Jacob is playing a joke on you?
Is he even in the house?
I haven’t seen him since I got home from school.
Put him into one of those group text things and ask.
Sighing, Rebecca starts a group text with her brother and mom.
Jacob, if you’re messing with me, I will make you pay.
I swear on ALL THAT IS HOLY.
What?
Don’t play dumb with me!
Where is that creepy gnome Mom bought?
Why’d you move it?!
What creepy gnome? What are you talking about?
Jacob, are you home?
Yeah. I’m in my room.
Rebecca, can you keep it down? I’m trying to do homework.
I’m not doing anything! I’m in the kitchen.
What?? Then who’s running down the hall?
THAT IS NOT FUNNY.
NEITHER OF YOU ARE FUNNY.
Honey, I’m at work. I’m not playing jokes.
If you’re at work, and Rebecca is downstairs…
WHO IS RUNNING DOWN THE HALL?
That’s it. I’m going to find this stupid gnome and burn it.
Don’t you dare!
Sorry, I can’t hear you. I’m looking for the matches.
Guys…something’s rattling my door…
Jacob moves from his desk and kneels next to his door.
He looks under it.
Seriously. What’s going on?
Beck, did you put something next to my door?
I can see two red feet.
They look really small and there’s something really creepy about them.
See?? I told you, Mom.
It’s the gnome. It’s evil or something.
That’s not funny.
That’s what I’ve been trying to say!
Stay in your room, J. I’m coming up.
This is ridiculous. It’s just a toy.
Do you know how many horror movies involve a possessed toy?
This is what you get for buying knock-offs.
Guys…I think it’s moving…
Rebecca looks up as tiny steps pitter-patter across the floor above her head.
I think it’s going toward the attic.
Good lord, just get out of the house!
I think you’re right.
I’m getting a shovel.
Hurry. I can’t hear or see it anymore.
Don’t leave your room. I have to run into the garage for the shovel.
That’s it, I’m leaving work and coming home.
Should we call the cops?
And say what? That there’s a toy running loose in our house?
It sounds dumb when you put it like that.
That’s exactly what they’ll think — that it’s a stupid prank or something.
Sit tight. I’ve got the shovel. I’m coming.
Rebecca climbs the stairs, the shovel in one hand and her phone in the other.
The hallway is empty.
The stairs to the attic are lowered.
It’s definitely in the attic.
How did it even get up there?
Under no circumstances are you to go into the attic.
Maybe if I can get over there and close the stairs, we can trap it?
And then what?
We burn the house down.
REBECCA.
Guys…I hear it over my room.
Oh no…
Isn’t the secondary attic entrance in your room?
Screw this, I’m going up there.
Someone needs to destroy this little monster.
Beck…it’s right above me!
Okay, I’m almost up the stairs.
Stop it right now!
Oh, I’m going to stop this thing all right.
At the top of the attic stairs, Rebecca sees movement in the shadows.
It’s small, but fast.
I think it has…a knife.
OMG, it definitely has a knife!!
Rebecca Marie, get out of that attic right this instant!
I’m coming, Beck…
I want to help.
I can’t text and fight this thing. BRB.
REBECCA!
Mom, I hear her cursing.
Something just hit the floor hard enough to shake the house.
Get up there and help your sister!
Everything goes silent in the house.
I…I think I got it.
I smashed that little sucker with the shovel.
He was fast, but not that fast.
But I think he got me. I’m…bleeding.
A lot.
Oh no.
I’m almost there. Hang on.
5 minutes later
I brought her down to the kitchen, Mom.
The gash is nasty, but I don’t think it needs stitches.
She’s applying pressure to the wound, so I’m gonna run up to get the pieces of the gnome.
I think that’s hardly important right now. Your sister’s BLEEDING.
I’m almost home. Just wait until I get there.
No. I have to get the pieces.
Who knows what a magic, evil gnome is capable of?
What if it can heal itself?
Rebecca thinks we should burn it and I agree.
Up in the attic, Jacob squints into the darkness.
The lightbulb has gone out.
He can barely see anything.
He uses the flashlight on his phone to finally locate the smashed pieces.
Got it. Beck, did you get the fire going?
Yeah, hurry!
Jacob races down to the family room.
He tosses the red plaster pieces into the fire.
For an instant, the fire turns an eerie shade of green…
And a screeching noise fills the house.
But then everything goes quiet and the siblings feel…
Safe.
All is calm, all is bright.
